And, since the numbers E , F by
             multiplying themselves respectively have made the numbers G , K , and by multiplying the numbers G , K respectively have made the numbers L , O , [ VIII. 2, Por.
             ] therefore both G , K and L , O are prime to one another. [ VII. 27 ]

But it was also proved that,  as G is to H , so is A to L ;
              therefore, ex aequali ,  as G is to K , so is A to
                 B . [ VII. 14 ]

For, as many as A , B , C , D are in multitude, let so many numbers G , H , K , L , the least of those which have the same ratio with A , C , D , B , be taken; [ VII. 33
             ] therefore the extremes of them G , L are
             prime to one another. [ VIII. 3 ]

And since, as C is to D , so is A to E , and C measures
               D , therefore A also measures E . [ VII. Def. 20
             ]

And, since C measures D , and, as C is to D , so is A to
               H , therefore A also measures H , [ VII. Def. 20
             ] so that A measures B also. Q. E. D.

But it was also proved that,  as D is to F , so is A to G ;
              therefore also, as A is to G , so is
               G to B .
